						"active": true,
						"timeZone": "America/Los_Angeles"
					},
					"body": "{html}<div><p>Can already be done by creating independent search bar and\npopulating a table with results from it. Tableview searchbars are\ntied to tableview data.</p></div>{html}",
					"updateAuthor": {
						"name": "stephentramer",
						"key": "stephentramer",
						"displayName": "Stephen Tramer",
						"active": true,
						"timeZone": "America/Los_Angeles"
					},
					"created": "2011-04-15T03:32:04.000+0000",
					"updated": "2011-04-15T03:32:04.000+0000"
				},
				{
					"id": "129625",
					"author": {
						"name": "mofle",
						"key": "mofle",
						"displayName": "Sindre Sorhus",
						"active": true,
						"timeZone": "Europe/Oslo"
					},
					"body": "{html}<div><p>Yes, I know, but it still would be useful if we could attach a\nsearchBar to a tableView and still get results from a source and\nthen fill the tableView. By having the searchBar attached to the\ntableView it can be hidden by default, and visible when the\ntableView is scrolled down. You can see this behavior in Mail,\nNotes and Calendar.</p></div>{html}",
					"updateAuthor": {
						"name": "mofle",
						"key": "mofle",
						"displayName": "Sindre Sorhus",
						"active": true,
						"timeZone": "Europe/Oslo"
					},
					"created": "2011-04-15T03:32:05.000+0000",
					"updated": "2011-04-15T03:32:05.000+0000"
				},
